**Abstract:**
A major essay dated May 21, 1993, titled "An interpretation of the Medieval's problem." The document analyzes the shift from biblical-historical theology to scientific-systematic theology, contrasting Roger Bacon's complaint that Sententiae supplanted Scripture with Aquinas's view of this as progress. It argues that "Aristotelianism" introduced the spirit of independent reason and reason-evidentialism, which transformed the practical-religious reading of Scripture into a scientialis reading. The essay develops a speech-act analysis showing how the articuli fidei were misread as statements rather than sedimented speech acts, and how the biblical narrative world was reduced to an intelligible system.

**AI Recommendation:** Central essay for the Chantilly project; provides detailed analysis of how Aristotelianism transformed medieval theology and the understanding of Scripture.

